**CELEBRATING WILL COUNTY PSC GRADUATES IN THE PROGRAM'S LARGEST GRADUATION EVENT TO-DATE**

&nbsp;  

  Will County Problem-Solving Courts celebrated the **graduation of 29 participants** on September 26, 2024, at the Renaissance Center in Joliet, IL. Participants included 18 graduates from Will County’s Drug Treatment Court, six graduates from Mental Health Treatment Court, and five graduates from Veterans Court. Approximately 200 attendees were present to celebrate the graduates at the largest event in Will County Problem-Solving Courts’ history!

&nbsp;  

  The graduation event featured keynote speeches from Mary Kay O’Brien, Illinois Supreme Court Justice, James Glasgow, Will County State’s Attorney, Michael Renzi, Will County Public Defender, Frederick Harvey, Will County Associate Judge and Presiding Judge of the Problem-Solving Courts, and Dr. Scott DuBois, Will County Problem-Solving Courts Coordinator. In her remarks, O’Brien lauded the graduates’ hard work, commitment to change, and success on their journeys, saying “I hope you know today that we are all very proud of you. **You are reaching the potential that you have always had.**”

&nbsp;  

<img src="https://ari.icjia-api.cloud/uploads/willcograduation01-min-20241021T14322151.jpg"
     alt="Attendees at the Will County Problem-Solving Courts graduation on September 26th."
     style="float: left; margin-right: 10px;" />

  All 29 graduates also chose to share a few words after accepting graduation plaques and coins on stage. Graduates spoke of their **gratitude** for the program and the recovery they have found. Their experience, as shared in their own words (Vital Voices), serves to **motivate and inspire current problem-solving court participants and future graduates** who were also in attendance.

&nbsp;

*Photo (left): Attendees at the Will County Problem-Solving Courts graduation (September 26) listen to keynote remarks, addressing recent graduates, from Presiding Judge Frederick Harvey.*

&nbsp;  

  Will County joined the Adult Redeploy Illinois (ARI) network in February 2015 to enhance and expand community-based treatment and services offered by its Problem-Solving Courts to participants with substance use and mental health disorders who would otherwise face a prison sentence. Will County ARI provides its participants with access to a broad range of services including substance use disorder treatment, cognitive behavioral therapy, and recovery support, in addition to enhancing the overall well-being of participants as they make significant life changes by providing transportation assistance, financial support for vocational training, and access to housing. 

&nbsp;  

  To our Will County graduates, from all of us at ARI, **congratulations**!

**CELEBRATING McLEAN COUNTY ARI GRADUATE CHRISTI P.**

*Christi participated in the McLean County Adult Redeploy Illinois (ARI) Program and first shared her journey of pain, perseverance, and progress with ARI in early Spring 2022 as part of the Vital Voices initiative to hear directly from those most impacted by ARI-funded programs. Excerpts from Christi’s story are shared below. To read Christi’s full story in her own words, please [click here](https://ari.icjia-api.cloud/uploads/Christi-ImpactStory-final-20240209T16345293.pdf).*

&nbsp;

<img src="https://ari.icjia-api.cloud/uploads/ChristiYMCAStrivev3-20240209T16551952.jpg"
     alt="Christi P., Graduate of McLean County ARI. Photo taken by YWCA Strive."
     style="float: left; margin-right: 10px;" />

  My name is **Christi P.**, and I am a 37-year-old married mother of 3 and I have a beautiful dog named Sasha. I am a recovering addict. September 6th, 2020 is my clean day. I have been off of heroin since November 11th, 2016 which is a huge deal to me! I am telling you this because all of my criminal charges were results from my drug use. I caught my first criminal charge in 2010. I was still learning and new in what was about to be my life. Several years later I was deeper in my addiction and my charges started getting bigger. Consequences started getting more serious, more damaging. I could not get a job or housing anywhere. I racked up some charges, I was in and out of jail more times than I can tell you. I was offered all different kinds of pleas. I took them, always trying to get out of jail or take the easy road. Which in the end always seems to be the longest and hardest road that never ended well and almost always an epic fail. During all of that time, I had a lot of lessons and blessings and curses. **Because I have been through so much, I have seen and done so much. I have learned so much good and bad.**

&nbsp;

*Photo (left): Christi P., Graduate of McLean County ARI. Photo taken by YWCA Strive.*

&nbsp;

  When I started probation, I had to go in every week. I complained, **but I did it**. I have done everything I was supposed to do. As time goes along, when you are compliant, they give you more space to do whatever with in your terms. But even though I do not have to be seen as often as I do, I chose to keep my appointments as every 2 weeks for me. It helps me to be accountable with someone else. And I like my probation officer and there are only a few I like enough to want to see them more than I am required. I have always been against every person of the law. I never imagined I would rather talk to my probation officer than my old friends. I have not completed probation yet, but I am going to. **I am not letting anything interfere.** When I am struggling, they check in with me and even better, they drop in on me [in person]. The funny part is, I think about them coming, and then they do stop by.

&nbsp;

<img src="https://ari.icjia-api.cloud/uploads/ChristiYMCAStriveGraduationv3-20240209T16554701.jpg"
     alt="Christi P., Graduate of McLean County ARI. Photo taken by YWCA Strive upon Christi's graduation from their Employment Skills program."
     style="float: right; margin-left: 10px;" />

*Photo (right): Christi P., Graduate of McLean County ARI. Photo taken by YWCA Strive upon Christi’s graduation from their Employment Skills program.*

&nbsp;

  For once in my life, **I am happy and proud of who I am**. I have went through extreme hell to get here but I am so grateful I did. I also hope & pray that my probation officer doesn’t go anywhere until I get off, because I hate change! I am grateful that I got probation instead of going to prison because I can assure you that had I went to prison, nothing would have changed. It probably would have gotten much worse. I would have used and ended up dead or back in prison. 

&nbsp;

  But I am not picking up again and I am not going to jail again for anything. I love having one of my children home with me, to have a home, and a vehicle. This has been a huge blessing (even though it sucks on the legal part). But **a lot of good things have happened to me, and for me.**

&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

*To read Christi’s full story in her own words, please [click here](https://ari.icjia-api.cloud/uploads/Christi-ImpactStory-final-20240209T16345293.pdf).*

*UPDATE: Christi P. completed probation successfully – and celebrated three years of sobriety – in September 2023 as a graduate of McLean County ARI.  **Congratulations!***
